On Wed, Jun 6, 2012 at 1:30 PM, Tamás Nepusz <
reply@reply.github.com

> wrote:
> 
> Fixed a bug that can be triggered in the current trunk version as follows:
> 1. Create a SAXDocumentReader with a tag handler T that has no subhandlers.
> 2. Create an XML file where the tag T handled by the above tag handler has
>    some subtags that should be ignored.
> 3. When parsing the tag T in TagHandler.startTag, the method returns with
>    the same tag handler when it encounters a subtag instead of the ignore
>    handler. This puts the context stack out of sync with the XML tree and
>    sooner or later one will encounter an EmptyStackException when the parser
>    tries to peek into the stack.
> 
> This commit fixes the issue by modifying TagHandler to return the ignore
> handler instead of "this" when a tag handler has no subtag handlers and it
> encounters a subtag.
>

Can you tell me a bit more about your use-case so I have a better idea of your goals?

Yes of course, sorry if my question is not crystal clear.
For example, here is the xml I want to parse : 

``` xml
<books>
  <book>
    <title>The Hobbit</title>
    <synopsis>
        A little guy goes on an adventure, 
        finds ring, comes back.
    </synopsis>
  </book>
  <book>
    <title>The Lord of the Rings</title>
    <synopsis>
        A couple of little guys go on an adventure, 
        lose ring, come back.
    </synopsis>
  </book>
    <book>
     <title>Twilight</title>
     <synopsis>
         A vampire saga (...)
     </synopsis>
   </book>
</books>
```

and here is my reader java class : 

``` java
public class DSL4XMLSAXBookReader implements BookReader {

    private SAXDocumentReader<Books> reader;

    public DSL4XMLSAXBookReader() {
        reader = mappingOf("books", Books.class).to(
                tag("book", Book.class).with(
                        tag("title"),
                        tag("synopsis")
                )
        );
    }

    @Override
    public Books read(InputStream anInputStream) throws Exception {
        return reader.read(anInputStream, "utf-8");
    }
}
```

All is working very well, no problem. But if I want to put the synopsis in a SharedPreference (this is just an example) and not in a java class, can I do that ?

Thanks for your time :)

OK, I think I see what you mean - you want to invoke methods on an existing object, rather than instantiating a new object for the tag, right?

You have a few options -
1. Let DSL4XML build your objects, then post-process them to set shared prefs (nice and easy)
2. Do a bit of static trickery - using singletons or static methods inside the Book.class for example
3. bravely try the below...

While working on the first version of json parsing I introduced a mechanism that could be used to do what you want (factory objects passed to the json equivalent of a tag method). I didn't quite finish porting that back to the xml dsl, but I think the only thing missing is a static method in the SAXDocumentReader like:

```
public static <R> TagHandler<R> tag(String aTagName, Class<R> aClass, Factory<R,?> aFactory) {
return new TagHandler<R>(aTagName, aClass, aFactory);
}
```

You could add that static method yourself to your own class ...

The factory is a converter of sorts - it is called with the constructed value of the tag, giving it an opportunity to do some extra work and/or convert the type to something else. In your case the Factory would not do any conversion, it would just return the object it is given, but it could store your shared prefs, for example.

A couple of things worth noting:
1. I didn't actually complete this work for xml, so I haven't tested it
2. I am actually in the midst of a rewrite, attempting to make the DSL more consistent across all underlying parser implementations. At this point I can't really say what effect this will have on your needs...

Actually, by default I use SAX to parse XML files in my applications, but I wanted to test and know if there were other solutions, maybe not with better performances, but with a more readable code than the implementation of a SAX parser.

Finally I can conclude that the SAX parser is great in terms of performance, and that DSL is as good as SAX and more readable but only to map Java objects to XML files. If I want to execute so custom methods during the parsing, I should use SAX because it is maybe "simpler".

I understand that this use-case is not what DSL is primarily made for, and I still think this is a great API to parse XML on Android.

Thanks for your help, you have greatly advanced my research. Keep up the good work to rewrite DSL :)

Have a good day !
And thanks for the Factory tip to make custom methodes while parsing with DSL, I think this is the best of the three options.

Hi,

The DSL is a little bit lacking on the root node. You could probably do it like this:

```
mappingOf("gpx",XmlGPX.class).
    to(attributes("version","creator")).
    to(tag(...));
```

The "to" methods all return the same DocumentReader instance, so this should work, although I confess I haven't actually tried it.

I don't know what the rest of your document looks like, but unless you actually _need_ the xmlns values you could probably just ignore them (don't even try to map them). 

If you _do_ need them then you're going to run into trouble because I haven't yet implemented proper handling of namespaces - the result is that dsl4xml would try to map namespaced fields to java setter methods with invalid names (like setXmlns:xsi(String value)).
Ok, thanks for your answer. In fact I don't need the root attributes so my problem is obsolete.
what license would you like? Apache 2?
I consider using it in an Android app that needs modifications that would be uninteresting to most users and probably break backwards compatibility. A BSD/Public Domain licence would be the simplest.
